caption: Amazing! I recommend the doubles, jerk chicken wings & oxtail but I’m sure there are many other gems on the menu to try!

I love this spot! They serve splendid food, their menu is rich, The cook in that restaurant is a real pro, I love a lot eating all their dishes. The dishes are consistently fresh, the service towards the visitors  is good. I  go often to this place and I was never unhappy. I highly recommend it.

In terms of food, Cane is excellent. 4.5 stars for sure. Terrific Caribbean food -- no bad options on the menu either.  That being said, my order was completely butchered. I waited for 45 minutes on my order and was not offered any compensation, refund, etc. It was a terrible burden to an already heavy commute (drove from VERY far away). That burden was too much to overcome for the great food.
Horrible made us wait in the cold

Absolutely incredible take-out and service from Cane! Explosive flavors, great ingredients - just everything was perfect. They have nailed it on Trini flavors. If you like Caribbean, or even South Asian food, you will find something on the menu for you. One of the best meals I have had in Washington in recent years!

Elevated Trini cuisine.. I didn't even know that was possible!.. and they do a surprisingly excellent job at it. The doubles aren't the messy lump of grease I'm accustomed to, but the flavor is incredible. The roti is good enough to stand alone. The jerk wings have a nice level of heat and excellent flavor. I'll definitely dive deeper into their menu next time I'm in the DC area; I can't imagine the oxtails disappointing. Meanwhile, if you're a local, do me a favor and eat some Cane for me!
The best  restaurant in the history of chicken.
Awesome International Cuisine 👏 must eat 👌 still 😋 salivating
The best jerk wings you will EVER have!!!!!! Well seasoned, falls of the bone and they provide you with dressing (i think it’s ranch) on the side, to balance the jerk seasoning.
Delicious 😋
This spot always delivers. They have good dishes for fair prices, there is no waiting time even when the spot is loaded.

Cane food, service, and follow-up are fantastic! I wanted to pick up an order on a Sunday for my husband's birthday. They are closed that day, so I worked with Natasha and the chef to have the order ready for pick-up on Saturday, before the restaurant is open for carryout/delivery service. She walked through the best ways to re-heat and prep the food. It was absolutely fantastic! Our go-to is the omnivore Tiffin boxes and jerk wings. We also got a couple of quarts of the rum punch. ALL was outstanding as usual! Happy to support this amazing restaurant!!
Omg... Food is beyond delicious, portions more than adequate and the staff are like old friends.  It felt like I'd been there before.  Very welcoming!  Kind of pricey but worth it.

*COVID REVIEW*  6 stars, if I could.  I had never had Trinidadian food prior to this but felt a connection to it, being Indian. I was completely blown away by how thoughtfully prepared every dish was, how perfectly seasoned and flavored every dish was, and how perfectly packaged it was for delivery. The doubles was such a fun appetizer, the herbivore tiffin box was a real flashback to childhood (comfort food), and the crispy kale was a great balance to the rest of the meal which was very stew-y and heavy. I can't wait to visit Cane in person when this freakin pandemic is behind us so that I can get a cocktail and take in the sights & sounds.
Best Trinidadian food in DC!
What I consider the best food in D.C. it’s a must try, with really good drinks too!!!
One of the best Trinidadian Caribbean restaurant in the DMV area
Best geera (spice rub crispy pork belly), oxtail, and coconut rice I’ve had anywhere.
Wonderful, soul warning deliciousness. Have just about had all the dishes, and they are all uniquely nuanced, spiced as presented.
OMG.  The BEST Trinidadian restaurant I have been. My husband is Trini and he concurs. The wait is so worth it. When my husband wants to treat me, we go here.

Flavors are pretty good (though use of palm sugar seemed pervasive, including in the rice, which I personally dislike but recognize is in the afro-indo-carib tradition). Unfortunately this restaurant is very overpriced.

Found this place on Grub hub and decided to try it out. I ordered the Rice, Geera Pork, Pholourie and Crispy Kale. Delicious!!!!!!!!!! I had no idea what the  Pholourie was, lol just went off the picture and I really enjoyed them everything was great. The rice was so full of flavor I could eat it alone. Will definitely recommend this place for dining. Look forward to trying other dishes
Food is delicious and they have good customer services skills
This is a really wonderful place—one of the best delivery experiences I have had in DC. The oxtail is so, so good!

Run, do not walk, to this H Street staple. I ordered the all veggie bowl and jerk chicken wings late afternoon on a Saturday and was over the moon with how delicious everything was. The vegetarian dish was SO flavorful and the wing meat just fell off the bone. 🤤 I’m looking forward to ordering the dinner for two in the future, and patronizing the restaurant in-person whenever the pandemic has ended. Please support this incredible black-owner business! I would have pictures to share but gobbled everything up in about three seconds.
Got delivery and it was PHENOMENAL! The fish and omnivore meals were generous and delicious. The jerk wings blew my mind. Thank you!
The BEST Oxtails I’ve ever had in my entire life. Everything is worth the Hype
Highly recommend the tiffin boxes for takeout - super delicious!!
A TRUE trinidadian would say NO !

This was the best Caribbean food I’ve had in the DMV area.I got the oxtail, omivore box, and jerk wings. The oxtail was absolutely the star of the show but the rest of the food was outstanding. The bread that came with the box was addicting as well.  One recommendation for the restaurant is to use plastic carry out containers instead of paper. The curries were leaking through and falling out of the paper carry out boxes.

As a Trini, I was very excited to come to this place. I have only heard good things and I appreciated the rave reviews. This did satisfy my need for some good curry.  On one hand, I was impressed that this restaurant made Trinidadian food accessible to all people. On the other, it felt somewhat forced. The prices are very high because of Cane's desire to attract higher level clientele. They have succeeded on this front!  Now onto food: I enjoyed my Curry Channa and Aloo, it was good. The spice level was a bit low, for my liking, but that's what pepper sauce is for. I, however, was really craving a top-notch doubles when I went there. This is where the restaurant fell short, in my opinion. I felt that the barra (bread) was a bit flat, the channa was watery, and there was too much channa for the barra.  The baingan, on the other hand was really good! You could tell it was really well roasted and chunk'ed (sautee'd with seasonings).  All in all, I'll be going back! I have to support my fellow Trinis. Best of luck!
Yum yum yum yum yum

We’ve been here twice so far and it’s been great both times.  TL;DR - great food, long wait times after 6, oxtail sells out frequently, the chutneys are good but everything already has so much flavor you really don’t need them.  First though, if you come anytime after 6 be prepared for a pretty long wait time, they don’t take reservations and it can be anywhere from 30 minutes to over an hour.  The space is really small, and a bit cramped but it’s got a hole in the wall kind of atmosphere. You end up a little smushed against other customers but not so much that you’d be touching. The noise level is pretty loud, but not shouting level.  The food: we haven’t had something we didn’t like off the menu yet.  Oxtail: very tender, fairly flavorful, and falls off the bones. This sells out pretty often later in the night so come earlier if you want to try it! Has a good amount of fat on it though, so if you’re not a big fan of that probably not for you.  Crispy Kale: delicious mix of texture and flavors, the kale really is very crispy, reminiscent of the teas tire of dried seaweed without the chewiness. There are bugs of corn in here than are hard and crunchy and you don’t really get the strong flavor of kale at all. Great side to mellow out the heaviness of the butter and oxtail.  Hops: the bread itself is nothing amazing, a bit dry and cold - but the butter is unique. Has a smokey flavor that really gives it its own flavor as opposed to just plain butter, I liked it, my other half not so much so to each their own! It’s on the saltier side.  Eggplant choka: pretty good, nothing astounding, it was an eggplant purée with onions, was good to top on the hops and as a different taste to cut away from the heaviness of some of the other flavors.  Omnivore box: so good! All the components were super flavorful and the meat was very tender. We got beef and lamb and both were cooked really well. This was the first thing we tried from this restaurant and solidified our desire to come back a second time. We also got this with the chutneys but honestly everything had so many flavors already it wasn’t completely necessary but still helped to change things up.
Food and service were absolutely amazing!! I was so happy to see and visit this Trinidadian restaurant during my visit to DC.

Andru (the owner) was so amazing to work with for planning my team dinner with 14 people. He helped me understand the menu in advance so I could know how much to order for my large party. When we arrived, the service was outstanding. Tim and Jada took care of us and we never had to wait to for anything. That's usually very difficult to accomplish with a large party. Additionally, can we talk about the food? The food was outstanding. Presentation of everything was so good and more importantly, delicious. Was the best way to celebrate a great day with my team.
Best food in DC period

This place is TOP five. I'm really excited to see where it places on the city's top 100 restaurant list. The food is excellent. The service is great. It is very small though and wait times are very long. Usually around 2-3 hours. So he prepared for that. It's for sure worth the wait, put your name on the list and wander H street until you get the text your table is ready.

This restaurant is almost perfect. The only issue I have with this restaurant is the waiting list.  There's no way to make a reservation. You have to jump on the waiting list on Yelp and try to time it perfectly.  With that said, the food is delicious. The doubles made me want to cancel my entree order and just order four more orders of doubles. I could go there anytime and order doubles and eat them without getting anything else. They reminded me of some doubles I got in Brooklyn once, which is hard to find in DC. They had both flavor and spice that seemed to get better with every bite.  The curried meat was perfect. The curried chickpeas and potatoes were perfect. I left there happy to spend my money and would have paid more for less food. The food was delicious.  Be prepared to wait, but it is definitely worth the wait.
Food was delicious.  As a Caribbean American I am very particular with buying Caribbean food. This is far the best in the dmv area. Everything tastes extremely fresh.
Delicious food, great service — can’t wait to come back!!
A bit overpriced but there was no wait we went on a weekday evening and the service is good.
The food is awesome!! The place is small and they do not do take out or pick up orders. You must dine in but the service and food is fabulous.
Food at this venue was so so so good, don't  usually eat red meat but I had to try their oxtails, it looked too good 😜

Restaurant is small and cozy, which I liked. Also very lively. The staff was very nice and answered all our questions. Even talked to us while we waited for a table.  The bread was really good. The butter was spicy so not my thing, but I could still appreciate it. Loved the oxtail and rice. Surprisingly enjoyed the doubles (I don't really like cooked chickpeas). Shared those with the table and my friends enjoyed them as well. My drink (something with rum and ginger) was good. Not much alcohol and steep price, but enjoyable enough. Would definitely go again.

Unexpected flavors and presentation to say the least. If I were to connect it to something it would be closest to Indian, but still uniquely different.  The restaurant is small. Perhaps seating 25-30 people. The service was great as our guide helped us through the menu highlighting options. We went a tad wild and ordered all the sauces possible to test them out. They ranged from sweet to hot and were compliments of nearly each dish we ordered.  The hops are dinner rolls, but perfectly cooked, warm, large, and come with outstanding smokey butter - topped with special homemade smoked salt.  Doubles was the least impressive of the dishes that came out. It was fried bread with cumin spiced channa. The bread was soft and soggy, even at the edges. It was fine, but I wouldn't order it again.  The omnivore is an array of separate individual dishes which comes in a stack of metal dishes. It contains a few meats (beef - was incredible), (chicken - solid) and then multiple other vegetables. It was a great sampling of the flavors of the restaurant.  Overall I was impressed and would go back. It's tough to get into at the moment, but if you do, it's a great experience.
Kelsita! She served us tonight and went above and beyond. What an experience, will definitely be coming back for more!

Restaurant is small and cozy, which I liked. Also very lively. The staff was very nice and answered all our questions. Even talked to us while we waited for a table.  The bread was really good. The butter was spicy so not my thing, but I could still appreciate it. Loved the oxtail and rice. Surprisingly enjoyed the doubles (I don't really like cooked chickpeas). Shared those with the table and my friends enjoyed them as well. My drink (something with rum and ginger) was good. Not much alcohol and steep price, but enjoyable enough. Would definitely go again.
Great food. The wait was a little ridiculous. They don't have a lot of 4-tops. The channa and curry was very flavorful, and wait staff is attentive.
Delicious 😋😋😋 Great food & Great Service.

Such unique and high quality food! The flavors were so good. You have to get the wings and try the spicy drink (can’t remember what it’s called). Be prepared for a wait and tiny tables depending on your luck and the day.. but it’s so worth it!
This place is really good. Went without any real expectations, hadn’t heard about it - delicious food, delicious drinks. Super well cooked meat and unique flavors.

As a native of Trinidad I was super excited to visit Cane. Longing to enjoy my country cuisine, I was very disappointed after eating at Cane. The food was very bland and not seasoned as “Trini” food usually is. The curry chana and potato tasted like they used McCormick curry from giant instead of Chief Indian curry that is used for this Caribbean cuisine. The DMV area has multiple international markets that sell ingredients needed to execute this cuisine. The paratha was good! But overall I was highly disappointed and came in overly excited! Please do your research, get a new Naprima cuisine of Trinidad and Tobago cookbook. Local Americans may be fooled but a native knows her cuisine! Get it right please from a real Trini! Fix it
Trini food, dumb good!! Definitely coming back soon
Fantastic food. Great service. Get the omnivore for two.
Other than the small dining space, their Carribean dishes were delicious!
Phenomenal food! Another knock out meal by Chef Prime!
Best food in Dc
We've been at least six times. Everytime the service and food has been outstanding! We've ordered the same stuff each time. Doubles. Hops. omnivore tiffin box. Fish.

Bookmarked it back when the Washington Post's Tom Sietsema named it one of his top restaurants in DC on the 2019 Fall Dining Guide. And it is solid. The Channa Fritters with Fresh Chow and Tamarind Chutney is an excellent way to start, and then we got one of the carnivore tiffin boxes, with a beef curry, (split between two) and had plenty of leftovers. I would definitely go back and try again, as I love all of the Caribbean flavors, and the service (sat at the bar) was exceptional. My only minor complaint is that the chef was a bit heavy-handed on the salt the night I was there.
The most amazing food and service can be found at Cane. We had a group of four and shared several plates. The wings, pork, kale, ox tail, everything was phenomenal!  A must have in DC!

Food was good, yet pricey. That's just DC I guess. The oxtail fell right off the bone and the doubles had great flavor. Drinks, while good, were weak and way too expensive. The service was very good though; informative and not pushy. The space is small so you could be sitting elbow-to-elbow with your neighbors and it can get loud. Good to try, but not worth repeating in my opinion. I do wish I had tried the tiffins.

I came here on a Friday night, and I arrived before the other people who were supposed to come came. I sat down and waited for about ten minutes, and one of the waitresses told me parties don't get seated before the entire party arrives. I looked at the menu and decided to order before they arrived. I ordered the vegetarian tiffin boxes, which came with eggplant choka, tomato choka, lentils curry, potatoes curry, and paratha, as well as two chutneys. The food came out in a tower of tin boxes, and I enjoyed watching the tower become disassembled and unveiled. I loved both chokas, especially the eggplant because of its roasted flavor though it was slightly too salty. The lentils and potato curries were a bit bland and I dumped the green chutneys onto them, but they were tasty. too. The rest of my party eventually showed up, and it was a lot of food. The paratha was hot and soft, and it went well with the chokas and curries. The amount of food was a lot, and we got an extra paratha and eggplant choka. The bill came out to be around $52 post-tax and the three of us had leftovers. I would recommend it!
Food was great and so was the service from Kelsita! I will definitely be coming back
The food and service are amazing. I would highly recommend Cane. I loved the flavorful and creative dishes. A real gem.

I went just for doubles but added the eggplant. Had the pleasure of meeting chef Peter Prime upon entry. They were so kind, pleasant and helpful. When I tasted the doubles, omg, party in my mouth and great level of spice (optional). Eggplant was equally delicious. DEFINITELY returning to ensure I try ALL the vegan options. Call ahead for wait time

The FOOD is excellent, my family and I are originally from Trinidad, and it was nice too have food that reminds me of home. But the bartender is VERY nasty and the alcoholic drinks are watered down. I have been going to CANE since it opened and is very supportive, but this past weekend for the H street festival the FEMALE bartender was BEYOND nasty, I noticed she was nicer to the Caucasian customers, I was very patient and waited but again NASTY. The FOOD is excellent but the alcoholic DRINKS are watered down.  5 stars for Food and 1 star for alcoholic drinks.

I’m doing an expat stint in the Philippines so I’m always excited to try new places on my trips back to DC. Cane was the absolute best meal I had in the month I was home. We had the Trini-Asian five-spice drums and the omnivore tiffin. It was a great way to try a variety of dishes and there wasn’t one thing we didn’t completely love...we were basically doing the happy food dance throughout dinner. We fought over the last roti, it was that good. I also want to mention how friendly the service was - everything about the dining experience was wonderful and I can’t wait to go back!

Small bustling bistro on the H street corridor. Food was amazing from potato curry to jerked wings. Don’t skimp on the drinks or the home made ice cream. Moderate price point. The noise level was quite high, would be difficult to navigate for a patron with mobility challenges.
This is a must visit restaurant! Drinks to die for!

Went here on Saturday. Was a great experience Peter was a gracious host and Jade took great care of our table. She and Peter both took the time to describe the menu and made great suggestions. The jerk wings and Gera pork was a hit and the snapper was so good I had to order another one to take home for the family. The curry beef and chicken were also enjoyed by all as we ordered dishes to share. My personal favorite was oxtail I am used to it in a stew and the presentation was a nice surprise. Will be back for sure.
Great food! Great service!

I’ve never had Caribbean food of any kind. I was a bit skeptical going in, especially because I am vegetarian. I was blown away. We got the vegetarian Tiffan box, crispy kale, all the sauces and the Island Life cocktail. The cocktail was light and refreshing and the shrub was so flavorful. The curries were flavorful and went well it. The mango chutney, pineapple chow and culantro sauce were bomb. The bread was like nothing I have ever had. Really liked it mixed with everything. The kale was a great texture (a little on the spicy side). My friend had the wings and the doubles and loved both. I had a bite of the doubles that were great! 100% coming back! Thanks for the new experience.
Wonderful service and great food
Wings were prefect. The rest was also awesome.

What can I say about cane,it is very energetic and the food takes you to  a different culture and the manager is very sweet and welcoming.And if you don"t like the food than don't go and besides,they don't need your 2 cents to make a dollar(hope i said it right).
I got the omnivore... it was so good.. Cane’s food is the perfect comfort food
This place opened back in April and the people here are kind and friendly they went you to come in and dine there. Clean and healthy food
Staff was very pleasant.  Jerk wing had the signature pimento smoke with the right amount of heat.  Oxtail came right off the bone easy.

This my first time eating here. I will preface that I am Triniamerican so I  love Trini food. This place does not only disappoint. The food was delicious. Our waitress was knowledgeable and friendly. My drink was refreshing with a hint of heat. Our food was brought out in a timely manner. My husband and I  were stuffed when we left and we had leftovers.  The only thing we weren't excited about was the bread pudding we took home for dessert. There were 2 different sauces, one was dark and had raisins in it which I would expect to be in the actual bread pudding. Couple of caveats: 1. It is small in size. Don't expect to bring a large party without planning ahead. 2. They don't take reservations but they use a wait list which is a good alternative, again plan ahead. 3. It is pricey for some traditional Trini dishes but unfortunately we don't have that many good options for Trini food in DC. All in though I definitely would come back and recommend trying this restaurant out.

The food was so flavorful! As a Jamaican I’ve been waiting for a restaurant like this. We decided last minute to check it out and ordered the red snapper and jerk wings. Snapper was legendary and the wings fell off the bone. Cant wait to come back and try more things.
Love the food! Bar serves primarily run but, bartender is very knowledgeable.
Service, food, staff all good. Owner is real Trini, perfect. It is small but that just makes it cozy. You’re welcome.

My husband, a family friend and myself headed to Cane after booking ahead via Yelp. TBH the Yelp book ahead wasn't exactly aligned with the wait times, but we had a drink at Ethiopic while we waited. A lil honey wine ain't never hurt nobody. There will be a wait. There will be a wait. THERE WILL BE A WAIT. And it's oh so worth it! I was blown that the three of us ended up at the bar instead of a table where we could see each other's faces and chat, but the kind waitstaff, bartender and delicious food made up for everything you've read thus far. My husband is "Trini to di bone" and was so cute explaining all his favorite and known dishes on the menu. The waitstaff weighed in jovially affirming all his explanations while providing an Americanized twist so we understood all the deliciousness we were about to consume. We ordered so much food. The doubles were divine! The geera pork hit hard! And the omnivore paratha tiffin box was your standardly delicious bussupshot and curry beef and chicken. We could not finish it all. In fact, two days later we reheated the roti in the oven and went to town on the leftovers...it was STILL good. Even the pepper sauce (which is called Cane Juice) tasted similar to that my aunt in law makes from scratch. We also ordered the pepper pot, which was divinely stewed meat that melted in your mouth. This is not just real Carribean food, this is authentic Trinidadian food. My husband was in heaven and mentioned the need to bring the family chef here for her critique soon. We will be back! Don't sleep. Don't delay. Go to Cane today!  ...next time I'll get the escovetch because it looked liked it wanted me to eat it when the lady next to us landed her meal and the jerk wings because you know, I'm sure Chef Primeval did it better than these other wannabe Carribean places. 😂🤷🏾‍♀️
My Mom was a Trini and I felt like I was eating a meal prepared by her. Well done Cane!
The food was excellent as was the service. I've had the red snapper and the curry chicken and beef. The sides, potatoes, chana and bread were delicious. I'd come back again and again!!!

Waitlist beware: got on the waiting list at 5:30, party of 3. Was told we were 3rd in line and had a half hour wait. 7:20 rolls around, and we still haven't been seated. A thunderstorm is rolling in, so we are leaving.

Delicious food and cocktails! Mostly had small plates. The double is a great balance of sweet, sour, and spicy. The jerk wings were perfectly cooked with a slow building heat. I had a delightful cocktail with a pineapple shrub in it. I can't wait to go back and try more things!

Met up with friends to celebrate a friend’s birthday.  Went to Cane, the new popular Trini streetfood restaurant and run shop in the H Street Atlas district.  Pluses: food is phenomenal and very flavorful. The portions are perfect. The presentation is beautiful. The wait time for food to come out after order is reasonable. Not too long.  Menu limited which is good bc you don’t have too many choices to drive you crazy. Just pepperpt, oxtails or fish.  (See menu)  Or you can order either a meat eaters or a vegetarian array of small dishes that come out in a stacked colanders (see video)  And that comes with paratha roti skins.  There is also an array of chokas (cauliflower, tomato, eggplant, cabbage) (see photos)  Appetizers are poulouri &doubles or wings or cow heel soup (see photo)  Mehs :  They don’t take reservations so the wait can be over an hour (but you can get on the wait list via YELP)  We did and still waited 30 minutes to get seated and could not get a table even then but instead the bay window seat for large parties).  There is one large group table. One.  The bar only seats 4 so you cannot wait inside the venue for a table to come available so if it is raining and you got there by Uber you have to wait outside in the rain  There was a steady stream of people and folks lingering outside waiting for their table! It is very popular.  The price is reasonable but fish is market price and when we went a small whole crispy escovitch red snapper was $38 (see photo) and a large is $68!  Current and modern Soca and reggae music pipes overhead.  Overall, a great place to go but prepare for the wait.  You leave feeling full and satisfied.
Food was Amazing.  Both the fried Snapper and oxtail  platter were unforgettable.  Deducting one star for service and price, however the food is unbelievable.
Excellent food but long wait for a table

Asked my boyfriend to pick up some food for me...apparently they wouldn’t serve him. While he waited to speak to the manager, the bartender never approached him to take an order for a drink. Even after speaking to the manager (the joke) they insisted they couldn’t do food To-Go. Shameful that in 2019, my boyfriend who happens to be a special education teacher was unfairly profiled or the restaurant chose who to cater to and he somehow didn’t Fit the bill. Honestly, they deserve a negative star for the BS he put up with. 👎🏾👎🏾
Great food and drinks.  Really enjoyed the experience!
The vibe here is great. Food is unique and delicious. Snapper was perfectly cooked and the sauce was a fusion of everything I love about eating. Non-alcoholic drink options. Gluten free options.

This place is AMAZING!!! I am visiting DC from Florida and I researched the best local spots. Cane's restaurant was highly recommended and TRUST ME IT DIDN'T DISAPPOINT!  The staff makes you feel like family. Always checking on you and lots of laughs! I was impressed by the owner because he was approachable, quick to ask if we needed anything else and took the time to answer questions about the place. I love the atmosphere, good vibes, welcoming people, reggae, afro beats, and a splash of R&B. I ordered the carnival drink and my daughter had the sorrell; drinks were made to perfection!  STARTERS: I ordered the Pholourie and Hops. The Pholourie was light and delicious. The Hops is served with a spicy butter; it's just the right amount of spicy(not to hot but more flavorful)  MAIN DISH: I wish I could have sat down with the chef, he adds a little something special to each traditional dish. I ordered a small escovitched snapper which is served with a coconut lime rice. My sides were cabbage, and  eggplant. I couldn't finish it! It's not your normal escovited snapper. I'm going to try and mimick this dish at home, it was that good! My daughter had the pepper pot with the coconut lime rice and cabbage! The meat was tender and full of flavor and the rice was cooked just right.  We had to skip dessert..but I saw waiters serving ice cream cones...as much as we wanted to try it there was absolutely no room left in our tummies :p  TIPS: #1 Call ahead and get on the wait list. The place is packed and people are constantly trying to get in and soak up some good vibes and great food!  #2 Leave room for dessert ;)
What a great place. Fantastic service the people were amazing hats off to the chef
Hands down best food I the dmv
Great food!!!
Brought me back to the lower Antilles! Great food, service and overall vibe.
Not your typical Caribbean cuisine. It's West Indian food. Kinda pricey.

If there were 10 stars...Cane would deserve it...Peter ...the chef... is a food God....I had the snapper and it almost brought tears to my eyes it was so good... from the drinks to the music... the staff (Tim) we luv ya... the ambience.. need I mention the food... that place is amazing..... Arrive early.. might hav to wait as the restaurant is small and seating is limited... Trust... it is worth the wait....
Honestly I kinda hope this place stay a hidden gem. Those jerk wings and tiffin boxes... best chicken hands down
Really great food, and drink. Roti and curry taste just like in Trinidad.

Price and servings were very DC. Cane does offer some twist on the menu. Drinks are flavored with a kick but watered down by shots. I'll have to go one more time to really scout the menu but I'm not excited.

The food at canes is amazing, it's like someones grandmothers cooking in the kitchen, hits the taste buds right were they need to be touched. The atmospheres welcoming and a great island style, the hostes and staff make you feel right at home, Tasha was the bartender that made some of the beat drinks to make you get in a vibe you won't forget. Canes has a special place on my food heart. Thanks.
Many have tried to execute a sophisticated menu based on authentic caribbean fare.  Chef Prime at Cane has succeeded. I will back over and over again sir.
I absolutely love this place. The drinks are crafted perfectly, the food is delicious and I am looking forward to my next visit!
DC, treat yourself to this! Excellent service, excellent food!
Great food and drinks will be back.

This is a new spot that's going to have some growing pains.  First, we were told a 20 minute wait and left our phone number with the host. It was a nice day so we waited out front.  20 minutes turned into an hour and my guest noticed that others were just walking in and being seated.  Next, the food is decent at best, and extremely over priced. $19 for oxtails - and you only get two on this tiny plate.  I expected a nice sized bowl for that price.  Finally, they make a limited number of drinks - mostly Caribbean inspired. So if you're looking for a whiskey or anything like that, you'll have to settle for a rum and coke or some fruity type of drink.
The food is really good but my favorite was the ox tail. It's hard to do but when it's done right it's a treat. What a great addition to H St. I will be back for more!
Snapper was great. Give this a try.
A true taste of Trinidad! Island flavor done very well!! Order the doubles ! And the Tiffen box. Bonus .. an amazing cocktail selection with fresh juices.

Unfortunately the food was more American than West Indian. If the concept was just food I would say it was ok. But the concept was a Trini restaurant. The food tasted mediocre  . It was fresh.. but under seasoned and over priced. I was hopeful when it opened. I went on opening night and was extremely disappointed. The folks were very nice.. the drinks were good but far from anything traditional ... I’m sorry
Amazing drinks!! Food was delicious too!
Prime knocks it out of the park yet again. Looking forward the the rum flights coming soon.

This restaurant is a welcomed gem to DC! It takes you to an authentic Caribbean experience through thoughtful and well executed menus — the roti (OMG ... amazing!!) ... some vegetarian and vegan options as well. It is rare to have such high quality “street” food prepared with such creativity and precision in a casual and welcoming environment.  CANE  is a hit!
Authentic and well executed. Awesome staff. Love the concept. Drinks are great and wine list is short but very thoughtful. This place is worth the trip again and again.
